the fact Lake Urmia is no longer a lake, as its water level dropped to zero, causing a local ecological disaster in the western part of the country. The lake is what’s left from a larger salt water sea that was less than 10% to 15% larger than the current Sea of Galilee. Lake Urmia is one of the end of Ice Age lakes that occurred and expanded westward due to tectonic uplift. This lake could’ve been much larger, and has expanded many more times in the distant past.

This ancient lake went almost to Isfahan in the east; to Anzali in the north; and continued westward to the Astarabad plain beyond and into the modern mountainous Alborz range of Iran. With 5,705 sq mi, it was the second largest lake in Iran, and it is now home to the physical museums of Lake Urmia, Anzali and Ardehaleh Wetlands and Wetland and Wildlife Cultural Museum, Baladeh. Some fancy marshlands these days, in southern Iran.
